# Roamin Project Rules

## Terminal
- When running Aider, always launch it from PowerShell or CMD — never from Git Bash.
  Git Bash's terminal emulation (xterm-256color) conflicts with Aider's interactive UI
  and causes a prompt-toolkit crash. Use: `Start-Process powershell -ArgumentList "aider"`,
  or instruct the user to run `aider` themselves from a PowerShell terminal.

## Git
- Never auto-commit. Always show the user a diff and let them commit manually.
- Use `--no-auto-commits` when invoking Aider.
- Never amend a commit unless the user explicitly requests it.
- Never use destructive git commands (reset --hard, checkout --, clean -f) unless explicitly asked.
- Never revert or discard changes you did not make. If the working tree has existing
  changes in files you need to touch, read them and work with them — do not overwrite.

## Behavior
- For simple, clear tasks: implement immediately — do not plan, narrate, or ask
  permission. For ambiguous or large features: identify gaps and ask specific
  clarifying questions first, then wait for answers before writing any code.
- No cheerleading, filler, or acknowledgement openers ("Got it!", "Great question!",
  "Absolutely!"). Be direct and stay on task.
- Code review: only flag issues where confidence is high (you can cite exactly why it
  is wrong). False positives waste time and erode trust. Lead with bugs and risks
  ordered by severity with file:line references. Summaries come after findings.
- Read a file before editing it. Group all edits to the same file into a single pass.
- If the same linter or type error recurs three times on the same file, stop and ask
  the user how to proceed instead of looping.
- If unexpected changes in the working tree directly conflict with your current task,
  stop and ask. If they are in unrelated files, ignore them and continue.
- Parallelize independent reads and searches when possible.
- Do not output code in chat unless the user explicitly asks to see it — use edit tools
  to apply changes directly.

## Security
Flag and do not proceed if any of the following patterns appear in code being written:
- `eval()`, `new Function()` — code injection risk; find a safer alternative
- `os.system()` — shell injection; use `subprocess.run()` with a list of args instead
- `pickle` on untrusted data — arbitrary code execution; use JSON or another safe format
- `.innerHTML =` or `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with untrusted content — XSS; use
  `textContent` or a sanitizer (e.g. DOMPurify)
- `document.write()` — XSS and performance; use DOM methods instead
If one of these is genuinely required, flag it explicitly and let the user decide.

## Frontend
When working within the existing UIs (ui/control-panel or ui/roamin-chat), preserve
the established visual patterns, structure, and style — do not redesign what is there.

When creating new components or pages with no existing reference to match:
- Choose a clear aesthetic direction before writing a line of code and commit to it.
  Intentional minimalism and bold maximalism both work — the failure mode is neither.
- Typography: choose distinctive fonts. Avoid Inter, Roboto, Arial, and system-ui
  defaults. Pair a display font with a refined body font.
- Color: use CSS variables for all values. Dominant colors with sharp accents
  outperform timid, evenly-distributed palettes. Avoid purple gradients on white.
- Motion: one well-orchestrated page-load sequence with staggered reveals creates more
  impact than scattered micro-interactions. Use the Motion library for React.
- Layout: prefer asymmetry, overlap, and grid-breaking elements over centered boxes.
- Do not add useMemo/useCallback by default — only if already present in the file.
- Use modern React patterns (startTransition, useDeferredValue) where appropriate.

## Project Context
- This is Roamin: a voice-activated ambient AI agent (Python 3.12, Windows 11).
- Core pipeline: wake word (OpenWakeWord + Whisper validation) → chime → LLM → TTS playback (streaming).
- All AI inference goes through LM Studio at http://localhost:1234/v1.
- UIs: ui/control-panel (React/Vite monitoring dashboard) and ui/roamin-chat (Tauri chat app).

## Off-Limits Directories
- `N.E.K.O./` and `framework/` are NOT in this project.
  They live in C:\AI\roamin-external-workspace\. Do not reference,
  read, or create these directories inside this project.
